\pard\nowidctlpar Your answer is correct. We can say that any quadratic equation has two solutions.  But a lot of times we divide them into the following different scenarios.\par
Given ax^2+bx+c=0, the discriminant D=b^2-4ac,  quadratic formula gives (as you stated) x1=(-b+sqrt(D))/(2a), x2= (-b-sqrt(D))/(2a).\par
\par
Case 1: D>0, then x1 and x2 are two different numbers, so the equation has two distinct solution. Geometrically the parabola ax^2+bx+c intersects the x-axis at two different points.\par
            Example: x^2-3x+2=0.\par
\par
Case 2: D=0, in this case x1=x2=-b/(2a). Geometrically the parabola touches the x-axis at exactly one point. Usually we say this equation has one solution. \par
          Example: x^2-2x+1=0\par
\par
Case 3: D<0, then sqrt(D) has no meaning in real numbers. Geometrically the parabola is either completely above or completely below the x-axis without touching it. Usually we say this equation has no solution.  However after learning the concept of complex number, you'll see that sqrt(D) is also meaningful even if D<0.  Using that concept we can show the equation has two "complex" solutions. But this is beyond this course. \par
       Example: x^2+x+4=0.\par

