Consider a monomial (a polynomial having only one term) ax^n where a is a real number, n is a positive integer and x is the variable. We say a is the coefficient and n is the degree of the monomial. For example, for 5x^3 we say 5 is the coefficient while 3 is the degree.   A special case is when the monomial is just a number in this case the degree n=0.\par
\par
Now consider a polynomial with more than one terms. In other words, it consists several monomials.  For example,  P(x)=3x + 5 +6x^2.  Most properties of P(x) are determined by its highest degree monomial. So usually we would first reorganize the terms of P(x) so that the degrees of those monomials are in decreasing order: P(x) = 6x^2 + 3x  +5. \par
Now the degree of the first monomial (or the highest one) is defined to be the degree of the polynomial: degree(P(x)) = 2; and the coefficient of the first monomial is defined to be the leading coefficient of the polynomial.  As another example, Q(x) = -2 + 5x^2 - 3x + 4x^4 should be reorganized as Q(x) = 4x^4 + 5x^2 -3x -2 from which we can tell that its degree is 4 and leading coefficient is also 4.\par
\par
A polynomial equation is an equation that can be written as (after some moving around) P(x) =0 where P(x) is a polynomial.  For example,  2-3x = -4x^2 is a polynomial equation because it can written as 4x^2 - 3x + 2 =0.  The degree of a polynomial equation is defined to be the degree of the corresponding polynomial P(x). In this example because the degree of 4x^2-3x+2  is 2, we say it's a degree 2 polynomial equation which we usually refer to as a quadratic equation.  Another example,  2x^3+4 = 3x -3x^2 should be rewritten as 2x^3+3x^2-3x+4 = 0. And we then can see that it's a degree 3 polynomial equation which is often referred to as a cubic equation.\par
